deck_excerpt: Revolvers deck sucks until you add some guardragons.
deck_description: Based on Revolvera deck. Easily able to get out all 3 borrel link monsters (for eaxample) first turn but open to both improvement and strategy improvisation.  The opening turn typically begins with special summoning two Rokkets with either Boot Sector Launch, Gateway Dragon, Quick Revolve, etc. Then link summoning Romulus and adding Dragons Ravine to hand. Or if you opened with Destrudo: Chrystron Needlefiber and using him to special summon Rokket Synchron. Then you normal summon a Rokket, if you used Romulus, use Dragons Ravine to send Destrudo to the grave and special it out with its effect. Link summon the little guardragons to the zones your link monster points to. Elpy summons Darkness Metal who then let's you summon any Rokket from the grave. Use either Darkness metal and Romulus to link summon the link 2 guardragon to the other extra monster zone. Darkness Metal and Elpy to make Sawnborrel if you summoned needlefiber. Ptsy re summons Darkness Metal, who summons Romulus from the grave. Or another Rokket on the needlefiber route. Honestly I can't remember the rest of the combos at this point but you should get the idea.

deck_excerpt: Go second.  Crush your enemies.  See them driven before you. Hear the lamentations of their waifus.
deck_description: Earlier in the month, I uploaded a Danger Darkworld deck based around going second, breaking boards and OTKing. My friend submitted to me a challenge; he feels that Blue-eyes Dangers would be better at it than my version. That shot at my Dark World Bois aside, I concluded there might be merit to that idea and decided to try to make that version of the deck. This is that. - Go second - Break the board - OTK, ideally by giving them a 0 Def Big Foot in Def with Jackalope and Creature Swap then attacking with Chaos MAX  In all honesty, this version of the deck has a lot of marked similarities to the Dark World one, just with different faces. Different places. Instead of Grapha popping something on discard, it's Alternative popping something as it comes out. Instead of Snoww searching more resources, it's Melody. Instead of Dark World Dealings, we've got Trade-Ins (which makes me less nervous about running Lava Golem right from the start, lemme tell 'ya). I'm not 100% sure if it'll be better, but it certainly hits the same sweet spots. I just wonder if I'm not actually running enough of the Blue Eyes stuff to merit the change, but still think it'll be more than capable of doing what I need it to do. And the inclusion of one of my all-time favorite boss monsters (who can't be targeted so shove your Anchors up your rear, Sky Strikers) is a decidedly delectable plus. It actually makes an OTK safer, since you don't have to completely empty a board, only take away the annoying parts of the backrow and the most problematic monsters that will stop Big MAX from doing what he does best to that poor, unsuspecting Bigfoot. The downside, of course, is that you increase your chance for clogging. I know, a deck that is at least 40% Danger cards shouldn't feasibly be able to clog, but there you have it none the less. If I start with 2-3 Blue-Eyes White Dragons in hand, not only am I getting nothing from those unless I see Trade-In, I am also down two targets for Melody. It's a little worrying is all. But I want to try it like this first, with the classic numbers for Blue-Eyes, before I probably cut the titular monster to 2. I mean, MAX, Alternative, Levianeer, they're all targets as well. But I'm running them all at 1, so whether that becomes an issue or not will largely be up to the testing labs to figure out. In the end, I predict the numbers will definitely be changed with some of these cards, but I've got a good feeling about it.  And please, please, feel free to drop a comment with suggestions about how to make this deck better at it's job; breakin' boards and doin' work. Just don't bother telling me about how Called By The Grave should be in the main. It's not that I disagree, I just think that I've got enough effects to burn through one or two and still be able to do what needs doing, or to get into Azathot before things get too bad.

deck_excerpt: An easy OTK with Blue-Eyes Chaos MAX Dragon.
deck_description:
After a long time, I finally post a wonderful deck which is very easy to play and to win. Surprisingly, it is another Ritual Deck ;).
  • Blue-Eyes White Dragon: Of course, for the Ritual Summon of Blue-Eyes Chaos MAX Dragon.
  • Impcantation monsters: For searching Ritual Spells / Ritual Monsters and to shift control to your opponent for an OTK.
  • Manju of the Ten Thousand Hands: Same as the Impcantations: To search Ritual Spells / Ritual Monsters.
  • Knightmare Corruptor Iblee: The main reason for the 12 Link Monsters, she acts as a 0 DEF monster for an OTK, but also searchable. The only note is Special Summon her before any Impcantation monster because the Impcantations will block you from Link Summon, causing a problem in sending her to the GY. In that case, consider paying some LP if your opponent has any monster in Attack Position by attacking them, then Special Summon her for your opponent to win.
  • Blue-Eyes Chaos MAX Dragon: Well, there's not much to say. A 4000 ATK monster with self-protection and "double damage". It is the soul of this deck.
  • Impcantation Chalislime: A cool card for an Impcantation monster to be Special Summoned, but note that this can cause you a 2500 LP loss, but it can also act as destruction for one of your opponent's monster.
  • Shien's Spy: A card for shifting a monster to your opponent's field. Combine with a Blue-Eyes Chaos MAX Dragon on the field will result in an 8000 damage.
  • Mystic Box: Same as Shien's Spy, but although it can destroy 1 monster your opponent controls, it requires your opponent to have one. So if your opponent has no monster, this card can be a blank card. Otherwise, this can be a better Shien's Spy.
  • Preparation of Rites: Search Impcantation Chalislime and recover a Ritual Spell.
  • Chaos Form: A Ritual Spell that is specified for Ritual Summon "Chaos" / "Black Luster Soldier". It can banish Blue-Eyes White Dragon that Advanced Ritual Art sends to your GY.
  • Advance Ritual Art: As I said above, it can Ritual Summon with just 1 Blue-Eyes White Dragon in your Deck, and it can feed your GY for Chaos Form.
  • Impcantation Inception: Ritual Summon any monster with Impcantations, but also act as a Special Summon (from your Deck) for an Impcantation monster.
For the Extra Deck, the XYZ monster is for situations when you can't send any card to your opponent and you have 2+ Blue-Eyes Chaos MAX Dragon or your opponent has 4000- LP. Link monsters are for Knightmare Corruptor Iblee to Special Summon to your opponent's field.

deck_excerpt: 2nd of 3 decks by Marik Ishtar from the game Yu-Gi-Oh! Nightmare Troubadour! This deck name is also known as Roar of Ra
deck_description: Marik Ishtar runs an Immortality-Torture Deck, which focuses on slowly torturing his opponents and watching them squirm. In the theme of pain Marik Ishtar's cards slowly drain an opponent's strength, such as discarding their hand with "Helpoemer", lowering ATK with "Dark Jeroid" and inflicting effect damage with "Dark Snake Syndrome". Some of his cards, like "Nightmare Wheel" and "Viser Des", are based on torture machines. Marik Ishtar's Deck otherwise relies on a variety of powerful Trap Cards and Fiend-Type monsters and "The Winged Dragon of Ra" as his trump card. Marik Ishtar also uses some of the cards previously used by Rare Hunters such as "Jam Defender".

The  goal is to patiently wait until you send most of the Servants into the GY. I use most cards to put Wightprince to the GY, and send Skull Servant and The Lady in Wight (TLW) there as well. Do not banish them immediately. Wait until you get a better card for the summon or a Wightmare ,so you could special summon TLW for protection. Dont't be eager to attack, use the links and the xyz to either stall, or destroy your opponent's side of the field. Do not rush to use the spell/traps immediately, unless absolutely necessary. Ideally, you will end up with a setup in which you'll have King of the Skull Servants, TLW and a few traps for protection and the equip spells at the same time. While it is an OTK if done correctly, the optimal approach is to be carful and act accordingly to your opponent's actions. Feel free to add your ideas to this deck and have fun playing!

deck_excerpt: *FINAL VERSION*  +Pros:  Fun2play Can actually be very good in casual play  -Cons:  prone to handtraps and negates slow
deck_description:
*UPDATE*

I have updated this deck, once again. I've tried to focus the strategy of the deck more around getting both Blue-Eyes White Dragon and Dark Magician as fast and as efficient as possible either on the field or in the hand to fuse them. That is why I've cut out major fusion cards to make room for cards like One for One, Fortune Fairy Hakari and Dark Renewal to get more use out of Maiden with Eyes of Blue. Also I have replaced Dimension Guardian with Safe Zone, which is more of a personal choice, because both cards work the same way.   *I accidently deleted my detailed description about specific cards in this deck and why I use them ... so if you have any questions or suggestions about the deck please comment! Have a good day!*   This is my second Version of mixing my favourite Monsters Blue-Eyes White Dragon and Dark Magician together. This Version does not feature any Ritual Monster. If you want to see a deck profile which incorporates both Blue-eyes and DM Ritual Monsters you can check out my first Version of this deck "Blue-eyes Dark Magician" Why? 'Blue-eyes white Dragon' and 'Dark Magician' have always been one of my favourite Monsters in this game and I've always wanted to build a deck which incorporates both Monsters. I have already managed to build a deck like that, which is by no means competetive but it can be quite fun and even strong in casual play. Strategy The strategy hasn't really changed all that much from my first deck. The main goal is still to summon Dark Magician the Dragon Knight as fast as possible. Allthough he is not very easy to summon, once on the field he can protect all of your Spell and Trap-cards, like Dark Magical Circle or Eternal Soul. If you want to make your board with him even stronger you could side in Dimension Guardian(which can be protected from him aswell) and equip it to him so he can't be destroyed by battle or card effect. Once you have him on your board you don't have to worry about cards like Twin Twisters, Knightmare Phoenix or other annyoing cards. Also if your opponent wants to get rid of your Spells and Traps they need to deal with a 3000 ATK Monster first which may give you the advantage. Summary This deck will probably not win you any tournaments but I think it is really fun to play and acutually viable against certain match-ups. It's just so satisfying to swarm your board with 'Blue-eyes-' and 'Dark Magician-' Monsters and if you're lucky you can make pretty insane boards which can be annoying to deal with. I recommend you try it out yourself or give me some tips or suggestions on what I can improve. Please leave a comment, I would like to hear your thouhgts and opinions. I think that I have improved this deck idea once again by removing all the ritual monsters. Yes, I know this deck is supposed to be for fun and all the cool and strong Ritual monsters are not in here, but in my opinion this deck turned out to be quite strong. Yes, against certain match ups that use a lot of handtraps and negating this deck can be shut down easily if you negate all my core cards like Eternal, Circle, Rod etc. Regardless if you play against people who don't come at you with unbreakable first turn boards that feature tons of negates you actually stand a good chance and you can really do cool things with this deck. I, personally love it.

I know I've been away for a while but it's only because I've been busy, I've got some cool meta decks I created for you all I'd like to share. This is the first one, as most of us know the Brilliant Fusion hit on the banlist several banlists ago significant hurt the consistency of the Gem-Knight FTK. But the deck is still viable and this deck profile proves it. The deck is still super strong and can FTK going first and even going second the deck can get through one or two negates which is pretty good. I would say this deck is still a Tier 1 contender. In order to perform the FTK these are the steps I have gone through and came up with. I have come up with specific steps on doing the FTK after doing it constantly on ygopro and in real life. The first step is finding a way to summon to Link Spider. Also in your starting hand you either need Gem-Knight Obsidian or Gem-Knight Fusion. This is why Gem-Armadillo is helpful, you can normal summon it to add Obsidian if you don't have it, but also have a way to bring out a vanilla Gem-Knight for Link Spider. You will add the other one you don't have from Gem-Knight Phantom Quartz's effect later. You need a vanilla Gem-Knight in order to summon Link Spider, which also includes needing to be able to bring out at least 2 vanillas in the beginning with extenders like Rescue Rabbit, Unexpected Dai, Reasoning etc. this way you can go into Link Spider and use Link Spider's effect to summon another vanilla from your hand, or if you don't have one in your hand and have already got 2 more vanilla Gem-Knights plus the Link Spider then you're good to go for the next step. After this, you need to use the 2 vanillas you have or whatever 2 Gem- monsters you have on the field to go into Phantom Quartz under Link Spider and use Quartz's effect to add the other one you are missing from your hand (either Gem-Knight Fusion or Gem-Knight Obsidian). Then use Gem-Knight Fusion to fuse Phantom Quartz and the Obsidian to make Gem-Knight Zirconia and use Obsidian's effect to special summon Gem-Knight Tourmaline that you should have in your graveyard, from your graveyard. Then use these 3 to summon Curious, The Lightsworn Dominion and use her effect to send Block Dragon from your deck to graveyard, or if you already have Block Dragon in your hand you could send Gem-Knight Fusion or whatever will benefit your current situation. Your main goal in these first 3 steps is to make Curious so if you have a way to make it after making a Phantom Quartz instead of Link Spider or something else then make Curious and proceed from there. There can be very awkward situations and you have to figure out what it is you need in order to do these steps correctly. Anyways, after you make Curious, you need to banish 3 earth monsters from your graveyard to summon Block Dragon and use Block Dragon and Curious to go into Proxy Dragon. Once Proxy Dragon hits the field go ahead and use Block Dragon's effect to add another Gem-Knight Obsidian, a Crystal Rose, and Gem-Knight Lapis. Also, keep note that you MUST keep Gem-Knight Obsidian until the end, which I will explain later, otherwise you cannot pull off the FTK. Next, use Gem-Knight Fusion again (you need to recur it from the grave several times by banishing Gem-Knights from your grave) to fuse Proxy Dragon and the Gem-Knight Lapis you added off Block Dragon to go into Gem-Knight Seraphinite. Normal summon Crystal Rose and use its effect to send Gem-Knight Lazuli from your deck to graveyard and use her effect to add back the Lapis you just used for fusion material to summon Seraphinite. Now use Seraphinite and Crystal Rose (Renamed as Gem-Knight Lapis) to go into the second Phantom Quartz on the left extra monster zone. Go ahead and use Crystal Rose's second effect in graveyard to banish Seraphinite to special summon it underneath Phantom Quartz. Use Crystal Rose's effect again to send another Gem-Knight Lazuli from your deck to add back another vanilla from your grave to hand. Now special summon Block Dragon by banishing 3 earth monsters from your graveyard to the second to last right zone. Now use Phantom Quartz's second effect to pay 1000 life points to shuffle back into the deck the first banished Phantom Quartz that should have been banished off Gem-Knight Fusion's recur effect or Block Dragon's summon, a Gem-Knight Lazuli and any other banished Gem-Knight monster to summon Gem-Knight Lady Brilliant Diamond to left most zone where Phantom Quartz is pointing to. Now use Gem-Knight Fusion to fuse Gem-Knight Lapis in your hand plus the Obsidian you added off Block Dragon to fusion summon Gem-Knight Lady Lapis Lazuli in the middle zone where Phantom Quartz is pointing to. Use Obsidian's effect to special summon the Lapis in your grave to the right most zone. Now use Lady Lapis Lazuli's effect to send the second copy of herself from the extra deck to the graveyard to burn your opponent for 3000 life points. Then proceed to activate Lady Brilliant Diamond's effect to tribute the Lady Lapis Lazuli to summon Gem-Knight Master Diamond and use his effect to banish a Lady Lapis Lazuli to burn your opponent for another 3000 life points. Getting to the finale, use Block Dragon and Phantom Quartz to go into Knightmare Unicorn and pitch a card to shuffle back Master Diamond back into the extra deck. Now banish 3 earths again except the second Lady Lapis Lazuli to special summon Block Dragon again anywhere except under Unicorn. Use Gem-Knight Fusion to fuse the Crystal Rose that is renamed, the Gem-Knight Lapis on the field and another Gem-Knight in your hand to fusion summon Master Diamond again. Finally, activate Master Diamond's effect to banish the second Lady Lapis Lazuli in grave to burn your opponent for 2000 life points, which ends the game. Enjoy this tutorial and stick around for more.

deck_excerpt: Infinitrack manipulates the level of the monsters in order to summon high rank xyz monsters while being able to "revive" those xyz. The superdreadnaug
deck_description: Usually what i try to do is summon the Rank 11 Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Juggernaut Liebe with its effect after summoning Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Gustav Max and dealing 2000 points of damage for free(your  way of summoning Gustav is with the Heavy Freight Train Derricrane and Flying Pegasus Railroad Stampede or 2 Freight Trains). A perfect hand will lead to a perfect game, almost no way to beat you: you Will have a 6000/6000 Monster that(because of  Infinitrack Goliath) cannot be destroyed by card effects and a Cyber Dragon Infinity to block any major effects that would target your monsters. If you have 3 xyz monsters and no way to use their effects(no materials left), you should summon the big link monster with those 3 and start cleaning his board with both his effect and the effects of monsters you re-summon. This is about it. You will learn the rest as you play

deck_excerpt: Set monsters, flip summon, repeat!! This deck uses flips and the effects of the Subterror to repeat the flip effects in a way that can summon big mons
deck_description: Most of the strategy revolves around setting your flip monsters and using Subterror Guru to set the back down after using their effects, being able to also summon Subterror Behemoth Umastryx and World Legacy - "World Armor" in the process to have control over the board with big minions and strong effects that banish(Umastryx) or destroy(Krawler Spine) monsters. You should work with what u have, so if u can summon Umastryx u should link summon Subterror Behemoth Fiendess and start flip summoning to take advantage of her effects. If not u should try to controll the board and wait for a Guru so you can search Umastryx or a World Legacy's Mind Meld to activate your Krawler's second effect to summon Deus X-Krawler and another Krawler (depends on the situation but Spine or Axon are usually better as they provide a good defence) Golem Sentry can use the effect to turn itself face-down and start a combo with Umastryx, that can summon a second or even third one if you are lucky. Lastly, Tindangle Angel is used, of course, to special summon flip monsters from your hand, but its effect can be very usefull to bring out Umastryx for your hand or GY when there is no way to flip monsters face-down, becoming na easy way to start the combo wih the Subterror Fiendess You  will understand the deck as you play but these are some tips i can give for now.

deck_excerpt: Frog Marincess deck by YGO Lite
key improvement Cards: Summon Limit, Imperial Order, Struggle Battle, Kaiju (side).
deck_description: This elite Kozmo deck is designed to get you the W. Has been played by me for a while and I've recently finish perfecting it for meta. 12-0 deck that can easily combat meta decks. Summoning in and out of your big ships is the way to land a 1-2 turn OTK. With Dark Destroyer at 3, there are too many combos to name. Whether you want to go first or second is up to you because it can handle both but I think first plays better because of the negation/counter cards. You can end first with a tincan and call of haunted or go second using struggle battle amongst many other plays. This runs through stall decks that use cards like mind crush. This is my favorite deck because it is consistent pretty much all the time and I've had a couple of people ask me for it. Test it out. Get a feel for it with some hands in the simulator and on YGOPRO and see for yourself. This deck has quick plays with the same level or better as meta. Leave a comment and let me know what you think. Have fun and lets duel :)

deck_excerpt: Yami Marik's deck from the game Yu-Gi-Oh! Nightmare Troubadour!
deck_description: Yami Marik runs an Immortality-Torture Deck, which focuses on slowly torturing his opponents and watching them squirm. In the theme of pain Yami Marik's cards slowly drain an opponent's strength, such as discarding their hand with "Helpoemer" and lowering ATK with "Dark Jeroid". Some of his cards, like "Nightmare Wheel" and "Viser Des", are based on torture machines. Yami Marik's Deck otherwise relies on a variety of powerful Trap Cards, Fiend-Type monsters and "The Winged Dragon of Ra" as his trump card. Yami Marik also uses some of the cards previously used by Rare Hunters such as "Jam Defender".
Theres not much of a strategy just to help new players learn how to play

deck_excerpt: Zombie deck that focuses locking down your opponent as you negate their effects and prevent them from summoning, offering total control over the field
deck_description:
1. Use Uni-Zombie (get it out with Shiranui Solitaire as well), send Banshee to the Graveyard to get Zombie World out
  2. Send Glow-Up Bloom (with Foolish Burial, Uni-Zombie, Gozuki, or get it out with One For One then summon Linkuriboh) to get Doomking Balerdroch out.
  3. Get Rivalry of Warlords out to prevent your opponent from doing anything, since they can only control Zombies, they cannot summon anything else. - Use Doomking Balerdroch to negate effects and banish monsters when needed, since everything is Zombies, everything can trigger a chain (Ash is Zombie too!). - Balerdroch revives every turn as long as there's a field out (doesn't even need to be yours), so don't hesitate to use it as tribute or extra monster materials. - Keep Mezukis in the GY to revive when needed. Keep another Banshee in there as well case Zombie World is destroyed (Quick Effect!) - Swallow's Slash can destroy 2 cards, and if you banish Spiritmaster you can destroy an additional card. - Spectralsword can help Synchro summon when needed without requirements, get Archfiend Zombie-Skull to protect your monsters from card effects. - Vampire Sucker is a Link 2 and can help normal summon Balerdroch and draw a card when Special Summons occur. - Vampire Fraulein can be Special Summoned during any attack, so it's a solid defense that you can sacrifice LP to buff as much as possible. - If you can get Zombie World, Balerdroch and Vampire Sucker out, then Archfiend Zombie-Skull, then Black Rose Dragon, you can get a clean OTK. - Tatsunecro can help get out of bricked hands by getting a decent Synchro monster out.

deck_excerpt: Fun Spooky Dooty Non-Meta deck focused on getting a One Hit OTK really quickly. It's definitely not Meta but it has taken care of many Meta decks, so
deck_description:
The goal is simple, send as many Skull Servant and Wight cards to the graveyard, attack with one (or more) King of the Skull Servants with over 8000 ATK.
  • Use Uni-Zombie to get at least 3000 ATK for the King by sending a Wightprince to the GY, if you have one in your hand you can get to 6000 ATK in one turn.
  • One For One can help sending a monster to summon Wightprince, then summoning Linkuriboh or Relinquished Anima to get at least 4000 ATK, 6000 ATK if you discarded another Wightprince (and you can still do your Normal Summon).
  • Sending all 3 Wightprinces to the GY in the first turn with a Uni-Zombie and One For One in your hand guarantees no less than 9000 ATK for the King.
  • Wightprince can banish itself and two more cards to summon a King directly from the deck, use Burial From a DD to recover the lost 3000 ATK.
  • Wightmare can be discarded (+1000 ATK) to revive a King or Lady, or return a Servant or Wightmare to the GY (another +1000 ATK)
  • Equip Opti-Camouflage Armor to a King with high enough ATK to easily and quickly OTK your opponent with a single attack.
  • Lady in Wight, while it can protect your monsters from Spells, Traps and Attacks, could prevent you from equipping the Armor to the King, so be mindful.
  • Wightprincess, on top of sending a Wightprince to the GY when Summoned by any means (+3000 ATK) can also be tributed on either turn to massively decrease your opponent's monster's attack in a pinch (additional +1000 ATK).
There is no strategy, don't play this deck.

deck_excerpt: Light/dark spellcaster deck with silent magicians, performage engine, and spellbook engine.
deck_description: Using Spellbook of Knowledge and Wonder Wand on your monsters to draw cards and set up graveyard is the primary strategy. Your main boss monsters are Black Luster Soldier - Envoy of the Beginning, Silent Magician, Silent Magician LV8, Chaos Sorcerer, and Quintet Magician. Main target for Summoner Monk is Silent Magician LV4 if you have Level Up! in your hand, otherwise go with Performage Trick Clown and link/xyz. Some cards can brick hard (silent magician 8 im looking at you) but most of the time it works out.   Note I only have 1 Silent Magician in the deck despite it being one of the best cards. If you can afford it/are playing online, by all means play 3 copies. The cards in this deck are all the ones I currently have on me so this is the ratio I have it at. Feel free to experiment and let me know if you have any better ideas.

deck_excerpt: Wanted to update my deck list due to OCG limiting Salamangreat Gazelle to 1.
deck_description: Wanted to update my deck list due to OCG limiting Salamangreat Gazelle to 1. The changes I made are Flame Bufferlo, 2 gazelle, coyote, fusion of fire, 1 called by the grave, topologic bomber, Violet chimera came out. I put in 2 widget kids to combo/ special out a Salamangreat to trigger an effect like Fowl, combo with foxy/lady debug/ spinny effect from hand in order swarm and get your links/xyz out ( side note: widget kid to jack jag/falco act fowl effect makes it easier and quicker to get your dweller out to lock your opponent from using the graveyard which can be useful.) Cataclysmic Scorching Sunburner is an interesting card which activates when a fire monster on your side is destroyed to special it out and inflict half attack of a fire monster in your grave for burn damage and disrupt with 2600 atk . Salamangreat recurrence to the place of fusion of fire to recycle your Salamangreat's. Mole came in for coyote to use its effect to recycle 5 Salamangreat's back into the deck. As for the extra deck 2 Pyro Phoenix took the place of Violet Chimera and Topologic Bomber Dragon which is basically a Zorovoros with out the banish and gain attack effect but instead it has burn effect in which you be using effect 2 on it to burn your opponent when they link summon. The side is essentially the same except since some card came out and replaced other the only new additions are Crusadia Reclusia, Violet Chimera and Super Poly. I wanted to put in Number 101 and add another Fowl to make it easier to get Rank 4 xyz out but elected not to.
